Subject:
Geographic and linguistic patterns in Canadian literary publication, focusing on where Canadian-authored fictional works are published.

Topic:
Mapping the publication cities of Canadian novels, short story collections, and other fictional works in English and French using Wikidata.

Goal:
To visualize the “motion” of Canadian literature from authors to publication sites, and identify primary publishing centers. This geospatial mapping highlights how English- and French-language works circulate differently, revealing the infrastructure and dynamics of Canadian literary culture.



SPARQL Query:
SELECT DISTINCT 
  ?work ?workLabel
  ?author ?authorLabel
  ?language ?languageLabel
  ?pubPlace ?pubPlaceLabel
  ?pubPlace_lat ?pubPlace_lon
  ?publisher ?publisherLabel
  ?pubDate
WHERE {

  # Canadian authors
  ?author wdt:P27 wd:Q16.   # citizenship: Canada

  # Literary works (novels, fiction, short stories)
  ?work wdt:P50 ?author.
  ?work wdt:P31 ?workType.
  VALUES ?workType { 
    wd:Q7725634   # novel
    wd:Q8261      # fiction
    wd:Q49084     # short story collection
  }

  # Language (English or French)
  OPTIONAL { ?work wdt:P407 ?language. }
  FILTER(?language IN (wd:Q1860, wd:Q150)).  
  # English (Q1860), French (Q150)

  # Publication date (1900–present)
  OPTIONAL { ?work wdt:P577 ?pubDate. }
  FILTER(!BOUND(?pubDate) || YEAR(?pubDate) >= 1900)

  # Place of publication + coordinates
  ?work wdt:P291 ?pubPlace.
  ?pubPlace p:P625 ?coordinate_node.
  ?coordinate_node psv:P625 ?coordinate_value.
  ?coordinate_value wikibase:geoLatitude ?pubPlace_lat.
  ?coordinate_value wikibase:geoLongitude ?pubPlace_lon.

  # Publisher (optional)
  OPTIONAL { ?work wdt:P123 ?publisher. }
https://query.wikidata.org/#
  SERVICE wikibase:label { 
    bd:serviceParam wikibase:language "en,fr". 
  }
}
